 characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam de Hatton was born in 1228, in Hatton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Hatton, was 28 and his mother, Agnes de Dutton, was 20. He had at least 2 daughters with Maud Matilda de Bretargh. He died on 27 October 1260, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1228–27 October 1260":"1228–27. oktoober 1260","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1252–1310":"1252–1310","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1209–Female":"1209–Surnud","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","about 1228":"umbes 1228","27 October 1260":"27. oktoober 1260","1200":"1200","1310":"1310","1209":"1209","Hatton, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1228–27 October 1260":"1228–27. lokakuuta 1260","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1252–1310":"1252–1310","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1209–Female":"1209–Kuollut","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1228"